body:
While writing some test bench code i've detected some strange behaviour with strings that contain special characters as TAB, LF, CR, ESC etc. If these characters are contained natively or as escaped character (\t, \n, \ooo ...) in the string they will be translated into their octal escape representation \011, \012, which is then stored in the data array! If the string is build with a concatenation operator and explicit byte values, everything looks fine as expected.

The two strings in the following example should have the same content:
```
module strSpecials();
  string isOk   = {"A", 8'd9, "B", 8'd9, "C", 8'd9, 8'd27, "N", 8'd10, 8'd13};
  string failed = "A\tB	C\011\033\116\n\015";	// second space is a typed tab character
  initial begin
    $display("string[%3d]: %s", $size(isOk), isOk);
    // --> string[ 10]: A	B	C	^[N
    $display("string[%3d]: %s", $size(failed), failed);
    // --> string[ 28]: A\011B\011C\011\033N\012\015
  end
endmodule
```

Using (Windows 10, 64-bit versions from https://bleyer.org/icarus/)
Icarus Verilog version 12.0 (devel) (s20150603-965-g55e06db6) or
Icarus Verilog version 12.0 (devel) (s20150603-1110-g18392a46)
with options -g2009 or -g2012

